abstract = {Argues for an ecological approach to realism of confidence in general knowledge. It is stressed that choice of answer to almanac items and confidence judgments derive from knowledge of structures formed by adaptation to a natural environment. Two experiments, involving a total of 32 undergraduates, were conducted. Results show that when items are informally selected by human selectors, instructed to select items that differentiate between more and less knowledgeable Ss, there is poor calibration and the usual overconfidence phenomenon (OP). However, when the item selection is "debiased," and the objects to be compared in the almanac items are selected randomly from a natural environment, the OP disappears and good calibration and good resolution are observed. Results support an ecological approach to realism of confidence and suggest that general procedures for debiasing overconfidence may be unwarranted. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2006 APA, all rights reserved)},
